Today I'd like to show you the future of the way we make things.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be self-assembling, replicating and repairing themselves.
So I'm going to show you what I think is the current state of manufacturing, and then compare that to some natural systems.
So in the current state of manufacturing, we have skyscrapers -- two and a half years, 500,000 to a million parts, very complex, new technologies in steel, concrete, glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space -- five years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other side, if you look at the natural systems, we have proteins that have two million types, can fold in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
So that's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're extremely efficient, far more efficient than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They're much more efficient in terms of energy.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can repair themselves for longevity.
There's something super interesting about natural systems.
And if we can translate that into our built environment, then there's great potential for the way that we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to utilize self-assembly in our physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all of the complexity of what we want to build -- so our buildings and machines.
We need to decode that into simple sequences -- basically the DNA of how our buildings work.
Then we need programmable parts that can take that sequence and use that to fold up or reconfigure.
We need some energy to activate that, so that our parts can be programmed to fold up.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to guarantee that we successfully build what we want.
So I'm going to show you a number of projects that my colleagues and I are working on to achieve this self-assembling future.
The first two projects are the MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are large-scale reconfigurable robots -- 8 feet, 12 feet long proteins.
They're embedded in electromechanical devices, sensors.
You decode what you want to fold up into, into a sequence of angles -- so negative 120, negative 120, 0, 0, 120, negative 120 -- something like that; so a sequence of angles, or turns, and you send that sequence through the string.
Each unit takes its message -- so negative 120 -- it rotates, checks if it gets there and then passes the sequence to its neighbor.
There are many brilliant scientists, engineers, designers working on this project.
I think this project really brings to light: Is this really scalable?
I mean, thousands of dollars, lots of man hours made to make this eight-foot robot.
Can we really scale it up? Can we really embed robots into every part?
The next problem is to look at passive nature, or passively try to have reconfiguration programmability.
But it goes a step further, and it tries to do actual computation.
It basically embeds the most fundamental building block of computing, the digital logic gate, directly into the parts.
This is the NAND gate.
There's one tetrahedron on each gate that's going to compute, and there's two input tetrahedrons.
One of them is the input from the user, as you're building the bricks.
The other one is from the previous brick that was placed.
And then it gives you an output in 3D space.
This means that the user builds the bricks the way they want them to.
It computes based on what it did before and on your instructions.
Now it starts moving in three-dimensional space -- up or down.
So on the left-hand side, [1,1] input equals 0 output, which goes down.
On the right-hand side, [0,0] input is a 1 output, which goes up.
So what that really means is that our structures now contain the blueprints for what we want to build.
So all the information about what you want to build is embedded in it.
And that means that we have some form of self-replication.
In this case I call this self-guided replication, because your structure contains the exact blueprints.
If you have an error, you can replace a part.
All the local information is embedded to tell you how to fix it.
So you have something that climbs, reads it and outputs it one at a time.
It's directly embedded; there's no external instruction input.
The last project I'll show is called Biased Chains, and it's probably the most exciting example we have right now of passive self-assembly systems.
It has reconfigurability and programmability that makes it a completely passive system.
So basically you have a chain of elements.
Each element is identical, and they're biased.
Each chain, or each element, wants to turn right or left.
So if you're assembling a chain, you need to program it.
You're telling each unit if it should turn right or left.
And when you shake the chain, it then folds up into any configuration that you've programmed in -- so in this case, a spiral, or in this case, two cubes next to each other.
So basically you can program in three-dimensional space -- or one-dimensional, two-dimensional -- the chain is completely passive.
What does this tell us about the future?
I think it tells us that there's this possibility of self-assembly, replication, repair in our physical structures, our buildings, machines.
There's new programmability in these parts.
And from that you have new possibilities for computing.
We're going to have spatial computing.
Imagine that our buildings, our bridges, our machines, all of our bricks can actually compute.
What amazing parallel and distributed computing power and new design possibilities.
It's exciting potential.
I think the projects I've shown here are just a tiny step towards the future, if we implement these new technologies for a new self-assembling world.
Thank you.
