Recently, we've seen the effects of cyber attacks on the business world.
Data breaches at companies like JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target have caused losses of hundreds of millions, if not billions of dollars.
With a couple of such attacks, the entire world economy would collapse.
And the public sector has not been immune.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a very serious data breach at the US Office of Personnel Management.
Security clearance and fingerprint information was compromised, affecting 22 million employees.
And you may have heard of the attempt by state-sponsored hackers to use stolen data to influence election outcomes in a number of countries.
Two recent examples are the mass theft of data from the Bundestag and the theft of emails from the US Democratic National Committee.
The cyber threat is already affecting our democratic processes.
And it's going to get worse.
The more advanced computer technology is, the more vulnerable are the tools we use to protect our data.
In particular, a new type of computing technology, called quantum computing, leverages microscopic properties of nature to dramatically increase computing power.
It's so powerful that it can crack many of the encryption systems we use today.
So is it hopeless?
Should we start packing our digital survival gear for an upcoming data apocalypse?
I think, not yet.
Quantum computing is still in the labs, and it will take years for it to be put to practical use.
More important, there have been major breakthroughs in the field of encryption.
For me, this is a very exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned of our new-found ability to create quantum effects that don't exist in nature, I was thrilled.
I was thrilled by the idea of applying the fundamental laws of physics to advance encryption.
Today, a select group of companies and labs around the world, including mine, are taking this technology to practical applications.
That's right.
We're going to fight quantum with quantum.
How does that work?
First, let's take a quick tour of the world of encryption.
You'll need a briefcase, some important documents that you want to send your friend, James Bond, and a lock to keep it safe.
Because this material is top secret, we're going to use an advanced briefcase.
It has a special combination lock that, when closed, converts the contents of the documents to random numbers.
So you just put the documents inside, close the lock, at which point the documents have been converted to random numbers, and you send the briefcase to James.
While it's on its way, you call him to give him the code.
And once he gets the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decoded, and it's perfect, you're sending an encoded message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A fun example, but it does illustrate three things important for encryption.
The code -- we call this an encryption key.
You can think of it as a password.
The call to James to give him the code.
We call this key exchange.
This ensures that we get the encryption key securely to the right place.
And the lock that encodes and decodes the documents.
We call this an encryption algorithm.
Using the encryption key, it converts the contents of the document to random numbers.
A good algorithm can do this, and it's very difficult to crack the code without the key.
What makes algorithms so important is that if someone gets the briefcase and opens it without the encryption key and the encryption algorithm, they won't be able to read the documents.
All that's got is a bunch of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure method for key exchange to get the encryption key to the right place.
However, rapid increases in computational power are putting at risk many of the key exchange methods we use today.
Consider one of the very widely used systems today -- RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was estimated that it would take 40 trillion years to break a 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was broken.
As computers become more and more powerful, we need larger and larger codes.
Today we often use 2048 or 4096 bits.
As you can see, cryptographers and decoders are engaged in an ongoing battle to defeat each other.
And when quantum computers arrive in the next 10 to 15 years, they will even more rapidly crack the complex mathematical algorithms that underpin the encryption systems we use today.
In fact, quantum computers will turn our security castle into a house of cards at the touch.
We have to find a way to protect our castle.
A number of research institutes have emerged in recent years looking at how to use quantum effects to enhance encryption.
There have been some exciting breakthroughs.
Remember the three things important for encryption -- high-quality keys, secure key exchange and a strong algorithm?
However, advances in science and engineering are putting two of these priorities at risk.
First of all, the encryption keys.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But today, they're not truly random.
Currently, we build encryption keys from the frequencies of random numbers, generated from software, in what we call pseudo-random numbers.
Numbers generated by a program or a mathematical method will always have some, perhaps less obvious, pattern to them.
The less random the numbers are, or in scientific terms, the less entropy they contain, the easier they are to predict.
Recently, a number of casinos have been attacked in a creative way.
They shoot slot machines for a period of time, and then they analyze them.
The cyber criminals used reverse engineering to create the pseudo-random number generator behind the spinning wheels.
That gives them a good chance of predicting the rotation of the wheels and making a lot of money.
Similar risks apply to encryption keys.
Having a true random number generator is essential for secure encryption.
For years, researchers have been working on building true random number generators.
But most designs are either not random enough, fast enough, or difficult to reuse.
But the quantum world is truly random.
It's important to take advantage of this true randomness.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can produce an endless stream of random numbers at high speed.
There's no possibility of the casino crime I just talked about.
Several universities and companies around the world are focused on building true random number generators.
At my company, our quantum random number generator started life on a two meter by one meter optical table.
We then reduced it to the size of a box.
Today, it's possible to put it on a PCI card and plug it into a standard computer.
This is the world's fastest true random number generator.
It measures quantum effects to produce a billion random numbers per second.
It's in use today to improve security for cloud providers, banks and government agencies around the world.
(Applause) But even with a true random number generator, we still have the second big cyber threat: the problem of secure key exchange.
Current key exchange techniques are not resistant to quantum computers.
The quantum solution to this problem is called quantum key distribution or QKD, which leverages a fundamental, counterintuitive characteristic of quantum mechanics.
The act of looking at a microscopic particle changes that particle.
Let me give you an example to illustrate this.
Think again, give the code to James Bond.
But this time, instead of a call, we're going to use quantum effects on a laser to carry the code and send it to James over standard optical fiber.
We assume that Dr. No wants to get the code.
Luckily, Dr. No's attempt to intercept this quantum key will leave fingerprints that James and you can detect.
This way, the intercepted key is invalidated.
The keys left behind can provide strong data protection.
Because the security is based on the fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer, or any future supercomputer, won't be able to break it.
My team and I are collaborating with leading universities and the defense sector to evolve this exciting technology into the next generation of security products.
The Internet of Things is heralding a highly connected era, with 25-30 billion connected devices projected by 2020.
For the proper functioning of our societies in an IoT world, trust in the systems of these connected devices is essential.
We believe that quantum technology will be essential in building that trust, enabling us to fully benefit from the amazing innovations that are going to so enrich our lives.
Thank you.
