You all know the truth of what I'm going to say.
I think the intuition that inequality divides and corrupts societies dates back to before the French Revolution.
What's changed is that we can now look at the evidence, we can compare societies, more and less equal societies, and see what inequality does.
I'm going to show you some data and explain why that data does correlate.
But first, see how miserable our lives are.
(Laughter) I want to start with a paradox.
This shows you life expectancy against gross national income -- how rich countries are on average.
And you see the countries on the right, like Norway and the USA, are twice as rich as Israel, Greece, Portugal on the left.
But that doesn't affect their life expectancy at all.
There's no sign of a relationship.
But if we look within societies, there are big differences in health across societies.
This, again, is life expectancy.
These are small towns in England and Wales -- the poorest on the right, the richest on the left.
There's a big difference between the poor and the rest of us.
Even the people just below the top have worse health than the people at the top.
So income means something very important within our societies, and nothing between them.
The explanation of that paradox is that, within our societies, we're looking at relative income or social position, social status -- where we are in relation to each other and the size of the gaps between us.
And as soon as you have that idea, you should immediately wonder: What happens if we widen the differences, or if we close them, make the income differences bigger or smaller?
And that's what I'm going to tell you.
I'm not using any hypothetical data.
I'm taking data from the U.N. -- it's the same as the World Bank has -- on the scale of income differences in these rich, developed market democracies.
The method we've used, because it's easy to understand and you can download it, is to compare the income differences between the top 20 percent and the bottom 20 percent in each country.
And you see in the more equal countries on the left -- Japan, Finland, Norway, Sweden -- the top 20 percent are about three and a half, four times as rich as the bottom 20 percent.
But on the more unequal end -- U.K., Portugal, USA, Singapore -- the differences are twice as big.
On that measure, we are twice as unequal as some of the other successful market democracies.
Now I'm going to show you what that does to our societies.
We collected data on problems with social disparities, which are more common at the bottom of the social ladder.
Internationally comparable data on life expectancy, on kids' math and literacy scores, on infant mortality rates, homicide rates, proportion of the population in prison, teenage pregnancy rates, levels of trust, obesity, mental illness -- which in standard diagnostic classification includes drug and alcohol addiction -- and social mobility.
We put them all in one index.
They're all weighted equally.
A country's score is the average of these factors.
And you see it in relation to the measure of inequality I've just shown you, and I'll be going through the data over and over again.
The more unequal countries are doing worse on all sorts of social problems.
There's a very strong correlation.
But if you look at that same index of health and social problems in relation to GNP per capita, gross national income, there's nothing there, no correlation anymore.
We were a little bit worried that people might think we'd been choosing problems to suit our argument and just manufactured the evidence, so we also did a paper in the British Medical Journal on the UNICEF index of child well-being.
It has 40 different parts, summed up by others.
It includes whether kids can talk to their parents, whether they have books at home, what immunization rates are like, whether there's bullying at school.
Everything goes into it.
So here it is in relation to that same measure of inequality.
Children do worse in the more unequal societies.
Highly significant relationship.
But once again, if you look at child well-being in relation to national income per capita, there's no relationship, no indication of a relationship.
What all the data I've shown you so far says is the same thing.
The average well-being of our societies is no longer dependent on national income and economic growth.
They're very important in poorer countries, but not in the rich developed world.
And the differences between us and where we are in relation to each other now matter very much.
Now I'm going to show you some of the bits and pieces of our index.
